3. insignis nobilitas, &c. The reading and interpretation of this pas· sage are much disputed. As regards this sentence, ‘dignitatem’ has good MS. authority, but ‘dignationem' is very generally read. The latter word has always elsewhere in· Tacitus, and also in most other authors, much the same force as the former, and denotes a person's rank or position, or the con- sideration in which he is held: cp. c. 26, 1; ‘inponere imperatoris digna— tionem ' (H. 1. 52, 7), &c. The mean- ing would thus be ‘ distinguished rank or great services of parents award to some even as striplings (stronger than ‘iuvenem ' above) the position of a prince ’ (cp. ‘imperium adsignabunt,' H. 1. 30, 7).
